# Explain the manifest-driven btrfs subvolume install flow and show an example.
show_btrfs_manifest () {
cat <<'EOF' | yad --text-info --title=$"btrfs subvolume layout (manifest)" \
  --fontname="Monospace" --width=780 --height=620 --center --borders=10 --button=$"Close":0

 Refracta - btrfs subvolume layout via a manifest
 ================================================

 Install onto a btrfs disk that YOU partitioned and formatted, without the
 installer reformatting it. The installer learns your subvolume layout from a
 small manifest file on the disk, so any subvolume scheme works.

 STEPS
  1. Create partitions, run mkfs.btrfs, and create your subvolumes
     (the "Run GParted" / CLI partitioner buttons help with partitions).
  2. Put a manifest at the btrfs TOP LEVEL (subvolid=5), named:
        .refracta-btrfs-layout
     One line per subvolume:   <subvolume><TAB><mountpoint>
     ('#' begins a comment. Columns MUST be separated by a real TAB.)
  3. Back in the installer, tick "Do not format filesystems",
     then choose your btrfs partition as the root device.

 The installer then automatically:
   - mounts each subvolume at its mountpoint (parents before children),
   - uses the subvolume mapped to "/" as root,
   - writes /etc/fstab (every subvolume shares the partition UUID),
   - creates a RAM-sized, NoCoW swapfile in the @swap subvolume,
   - configures hibernation (resume= / resume_offset=).
 If no manifest is found but subvolumes exist, it falls back to discovering
 them and guessing mountpoints from their names.

 EXAMPLE  .refracta-btrfs-layout   (the gap in each line is a single TAB)
   # <subvolume>        <mountpoint>
   @rootfs              /
   @home                /home
   @var_log             /var/log
   @var_cache           /var/cache
   @libvirt_images      /var/lib/libvirt/images
   @swap                /swap
   @tmp                 /tmp
   @snapshots           /.snapshots

 CREATE IT BY HAND  (example device /dev/sdaX - adjust!)
   mkfs.btrfs -L btrfs-root /dev/sdaX
   mount -o subvolid=5 /dev/sdaX /mnt
   for s in @rootfs @home @var_log @var_cache @libvirt_images @swap @tmp @snapshots; do
       btrfs subvolume create /mnt/$s
   done
   printf '%s\t%s\n' \
     @rootfs / @home /home @var_log /var/log @var_cache /var/cache \
     @libvirt_images /var/lib/libvirt/images @swap /swap \
     @tmp /tmp @snapshots /.snapshots > /mnt/.refracta-btrfs-layout
   umount /mnt

 The project's disk_setup_for_btrfs_desktop_subvolumes.sh does all of the
 above for you (partitions, subvolumes, and the manifest).

EOF
}


